    <h1>Authentication in Web Applications</h1>
    <p><strong>Authentication</strong> is the process of verifying who a user is. In other words, it answers the question: <em>"Are you really who you say you are?"</em></p>

    <h2>Why Authentication is Important</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Protects sensitive information.</li>
        <li>Allows users to access personalized content.</li>
        <li>Prevents unauthorized access to your application.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example: Simple Login in ASP.NET Core</h2>
    <p>In ASP.NET Core, you can use <strong>Identity</strong> to handle authentication easily. Here’s a simplified example:</p>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Registering a User</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
// Model
public class RegisterModel
{
    public string Email { get; set; }
    public string Password { get; set; }
}

// Controller
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> Register(RegisterModel model)
{
    if (ModelState.IsValid)
    {
        var user = new IdentityUser { UserName = model.Email, Email = model.Email };
        var result = await _userManager.CreateAsync(user, model.Password);
        if (result.Succeeded)
        {
            await _signInManager.SignInAsync(user, isPersistent: false);
            return RedirectToAction("Index", "Home");
        }
    }
    return View(model);
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>How It Works</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>User provides their email and password.</li>
        <li>ASP.NET Identity checks if the user exists and if the password is correct.</li>
        <li>If valid, the user is logged in and can access protected pages.</li>
    </ul>

